# MissTest
[![Python](https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/tensorflow.svg?style=plastic)]() [![Coverage](https://img.shields.io/badge/coverage-60%25-brightgreen)]()[![Codecov test coverage](https://codecov.io/gh/r-lib/devtools/branch/main/graph/badge.svg)]()

Framework for determining the statistical properties of missing values in a dataset.

MissTests is a framework that, through statistical strategies, aims to determine to which class the missing values belong, in order to determine whether they are:

* Missing Completely At Random (MCAR): These are values that are missing randomly and have no relationship with any other variable in the dataset.
* Missing At Random (MAR): These are values that are missing randomly, but have a relationship with another variable in the dataset.
* Missing Not At Random (MNAR): These are values that are missing due to a reason or a mechanism that is related to the value itself, and not to any other variable in the dataset.


Given the above, the main objective is to develop a statistical inference model that can determine the category of missing values and based on that, generate rules such as:

1. Missing values less than 3% of the total set will be deleted in the case of MCAR.
2. For MCAR with missing values greater than 3% of the total set, strategies for imputing missing values will be proposed (to be determined).
3. For MAR and MNAR with missing values less than 3%, strategies for imputing data will be proposed for regression and classification problems with a base framework that seeks to understand the behavior of variance.
4. For MAR and MNAR with missing values greater than 3%, strategies for imputing data will be proposed for regression and classification problems with a base framework but with fine tuning to understand the behavior of variance.

Finally, a visualization design for these models will be presented.
